      <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Lemma 7.8.</strong> If  <span class="math">(P_&#123;\mathscr&#123;C&#125;&#125;, V_&#123;\mathscr&#123;C&#125;&#125;)</span>  is a linear PCPP such that Construction 7.5 yields (P, V) with perfect zero knowledge, then  <span class="math">(P_&#123;\mathscr&#123;C&#125;&#125;, V_&#123;\mathscr&#123;C&#125;&#125;)</span>  has a constraint detector that runs in probabilistic polynomial time. (In fact, the same statement holds even if the construction yields (P, V) with only statistical zero knowledge.)</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> The linear code  <span class="math">L_n := \&#123; w || P(n, w) \&#125;_&#123;w \in C_n&#125;</span>  has domain  <span class="math">D^<em>(n) := D(n) \sqcup [I_&#123;\mathscr&#123;C&#125;&#125;(n)]</span> , which is the disjoint union of D(n) (the domain of  <span class="math">C_n</span> ) and  <span class="math">[I_&#123;\mathscr&#123;C&#125;&#125;(n)]</span>  (the domain of  <span class="math">P(n, C_n)</span> ); see Definition 7.2. Let  <span class="math">I \subseteq D^</em>(n)</span> . We need, in probabilistic polynomial time, to output a basis for  <span class="math">(L_n|_I)^\perp</span> . Construct a malicious verifier  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;V&#125;</span>  that works as follows:</p>
