      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>Given  <span class="math">\alpha \in L_0'</span> ,  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125; \colon \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu,k]&#125; \to \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1),\mu,k]&#125;</span>  is the projection of  <span class="math">D^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu,k]</span>  on  <span class="math">D_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;</span>  with indices renamed to elements of  <span class="math">D^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1),\mu,k]</span> . Formally,  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;(w) = w'</span>  if and only if  <span class="math">w'(\phi_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;(x)) = w(x)</span>  for all  <span class="math">x \in D^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1),\mu,k]</span> .</li>
        <li>Given  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span> ,  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125; \colon \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu,k]&#125; \to \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L_&#123;\beta&#125;,\mu,k]&#125;</span>  is the projection of  <span class="math">D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu,k]</span>  on  <span class="math">D_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;</span>  with indices renamed to elements of  <span class="math">D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L_&#123;\beta&#125;,\mu,k]</span> . Formally,  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;(w) = w'</span>  if and only if  <span class="math">w'(\phi_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;(x)) = w(x)</span>  for all  <span class="math">x \in D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L_&#123;\beta&#125;,\mu,k]</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">The following definition considers a code that extends the evaluation of a univariate polynomial with a bivariate function that represents the polynomial over a specially-chosen set.</p>
      <span id="page-50-0"></span>**Definition F.2** (RS $_&#123;\square&#125;$ ). Given a field  $\mathbb&#123;F&#125;$ , a subfield  $\mathbb&#123;K&#125; \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125;$ , a  $\mathbb&#123;K&#125;$ -linear space  $L \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125;$ , and a positive integer  $\mu$ , the code RS $_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu]$  consists of all  $w \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu]&#125;$  such that  $f_w \colon D_&#123;\mathrm&#123;bi&#125;&#125; \to \mathbb&#123;F&#125;$  is an evaluation of a low degree polynomial: there exists a polynomial  $g \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;[X,Y]$  such that: (i)  $\deg_X(g) &lt; |L_0|$ , (ii)  $\deg_Y(g) &lt; |L_1| \cdot \rho[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,\mu]$ , (iii)  $g|_&#123;D_&#123;\mathrm&#123;bi&#125;&#125;&#125; = f_w$ .
      <p class="text-gray-300">Ben-Sasson and Sudhan [BS08] show that:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li><span class="math">v \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, |L| \cdot \rho]</span>  if and only if there exists  <span class="math">w \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  such that  <span class="math">w|_&#123;\&#123;\mathrm&#123;rs&#125;\&#125; \times L&#125; = v</span> ;</li>
        <li><span class="math">w \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  if and only if</li>
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in L'_0</span> ,  <span class="math">f_w|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)&#125; \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), |L_1| \cdot \rho]</span>  (with the standard mapping between domains) and for every  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span> ,  <span class="math">f_w|_&#123;L_\beta \times \&#123;Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)\&#125;&#125; \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_\beta, |L_0|]</span>  (with the standard mapping between domains).</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">The above equivalences illustrate the 'quadratic reduction' from testing that  <span class="math">w \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^L</span>  is a codeword of  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, |L| \cdot \rho]</span>  to a set of  <span class="math">\Theta(\sqrt&#123;|L|&#125;)</span>  problems of testing membership in codes of the form  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L', d']</span>  with  <span class="math">|L'|, d' = \Theta(\sqrt&#123;|L|&#125;)</span> .</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">The code from Definition F.2 corresponds to one step of the recursive construction of [BS08]. We now build on that definition, and recursively define the linear code family BS-RS.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Definition F.3</strong> (BS-RS). Given a field  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , a subfield  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125; \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , a  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;</span> -linear space  <span class="math">L \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , a positive integer  <span class="math">\mu</span> , and a positive integer  <span class="math">k &gt; 2\mu</span> , the code BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] consists of all words  <span class="math">w \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D^&#123;\mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]&#125;</span>  satisfying the following. If  <span class="math">\dim(L) \leq k</span>  then  <span class="math">w \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span> . If  <span class="math">\dim(L) &gt; k</span>  the following holds: (1) for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in L'_0</span>  there exists  <span class="math">w_\alpha \in \mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">w_\alpha(\phi_&#123;\mathrm&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;(x)) = w(x)</span>  for every  <span class="math">x \in D[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span> ; (2) for every  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span>  there exists  <span class="math">w_\beta \in \mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_\beta, \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">w_\beta(\phi_&#123;\mathrm&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;(x)) = w(x)</span>  for every  <span class="math">x \in D[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_\beta, \mu, k]</span> .</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">We conclude this section with two claims about BS-RS that we use in later sections. We omit the proof of the first claim (and refer the interested reader to [BS08]), and prove the second claim based on the first one.</p>
      <span id="page-50-1"></span>**Claim F.4.** For every codeword  $w \in RS[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, |L| \cdot \rho]$ , positive integer  $\mu$ , and positive integer  $k &gt; 2\mu$ , there exists a unique  $\pi_w$  such that  $w \circ \pi_w \in BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$ .
      <span id="page-50-2"></span>**Claim F.5.** The following two statements hold for the code BS-RS[ $\mathbb&#123;K&#125;$ ,  $\mathbb&#123;F&#125;$ , L,  $\mu$ , k]:
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in L'_0</span>  and  <span class="math">w' \in BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span>  there exists  <span class="math">w \in BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;, \alpha&#125;(w) = w'</span> ;</li>
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span>  and  <span class="math">w' \in BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k]</span>  there exists  <span class="math">w \in BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;row, \beta&#125;(w) = w'</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> The proofs for the two statements are similar, so we only give the proof for the first statement. Let  <span class="math">w' \in BS\text&#123;-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span> , and define  <span class="math">w_&#123;rs&#125; := w'|_&#123;\&#123;rs\&#125; \times Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)&#125;</span> ; observe that  <span class="math">w_&#123;rs&#125;</span>  in  <span class="math">RS[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), |L_1| \cdot \rho]</span> . By Claim F.4, w' is uniquely determined by  <span class="math">w_&#123;rs&#125;</span> , thus it suffices to show that there exists  <span class="math">w_&#123;\square&#125; \in RS_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  such that  <span class="math">f_&#123;w_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)&#125; = w_&#123;rs&#125;</span> . By definition of  <span class="math">RS_&#123;\square&#125;</span> , it suffices to show that there exists a bivariate polynomial  <span class="math">g \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;[X,Y]</span>  such that: (i)  <span class="math">\deg_X(g) &lt; |L_0|</span> , (ii)  <span class="math">\deg_Y(g) &lt; |L_1| \cdot \rho</span> , (iii)  <span class="math">g|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)&#125; = w_&#123;rs&#125; \in RS[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), |L_1| \cdot \rho]</span> . The existence of such g follows by considering a suitable interpolating set (see, e.g., Appendix H).</p>
      <h4 id="span-id-page-51-0-span-proof-of-lemma-4-27-g" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2"><span id="page-51-0"></span>Proof of Lemma 4.27 G</h4>
      <p class="text-gray-300">In this section we prove Lemma 4.27. In Appendix G.1 we define the recursive cover and prove its combinatorial properties; in Appendix G.2 we prove that a spanning set for the duals of codes in this cover can be computed efficiently; in Appendix G.3, we put these together to conclude the proof.</p>
      <h4 id="span-id-page-51-1-span-the-recursive-cover-and-its-combinatorial-properties" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2"><span id="page-51-1"></span>The recursive cover and its combinatorial properties</h4>
      <p class="text-gray-300">We define a recursive cover for BS-RS and then prove certain combinatorial properties for it. The definition relies on the definition of another cover, which we now introduce.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Definition G.1.</strong> The native cover  <span class="math">S[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  of BS-RS <span class="math">[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  is defined as follows:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>if  <span class="math">\dim(L) \le k</span>  then the cover contains only the trivial view  <span class="math">(D^&#123;\mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k], \mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k])</span> ;</li>
        <li>if  <span class="math">\dim(L) &gt; k</span>  then the cover contains</li>
        <li>the view (BS-RS[K, F,  <span class="math">Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k], D_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;</span> ) for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in L'_0</span> , and</li>
        <li>the view (BS-RS[K, F,  <span class="math">L_&#123;\beta&#125;</span> ,  <span class="math">\mu</span> , k],  <span class="math">D_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;</span> ) for every  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">We now prove that the native cover is indeed a cover.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Claim G.2.</strong> The native cover of BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;</span> ,  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , L,  <span class="math">\mu</span> , k] is a code cover (see Definition 4.13).</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> From Claim F.5 we know that:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in L'_0</span> , the restriction of BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] to  <span class="math">D_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;</span>  equals BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k</span> ];</li>
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span> , the restriction of BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] to  <span class="math">D_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;</span>  equals BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k</span> ].</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Therefore, it suffices to show that  <span class="math">D_&#123;\square&#125; \subseteq (\bigcup_&#123;\alpha \in L'_0&#125; D_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;) \cup (\bigcup_&#123;\beta \in L_1&#125; D_&#123;\operatorname&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;)</span> . So let x be an index in  <span class="math">D_&#123;\square&#125;</span> .</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>If there exists  <span class="math">\alpha \in L_0'</span>  such that  <span class="math">x \in \&#123;\text&#123;px&#125;\&#125; \times \&#123;(\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha)\&#125; \times D_&#123;\text&#123;pf&#125;&#125;^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span> , then  <span class="math">x \in D_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha&#125;</span> .</li>
      <p class="text-gray-300">If there exists  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span>  such that  <span class="math">x \in \&#123;\text&#123;px&#125;\&#125; \times \&#123;(\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta)\&#125; \times D_&#123;\text&#123;pf&#125;&#125;^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k]</span> , then  <span class="math">x \in D_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta&#125;</span> . If  <span class="math">x \in \&#123;\text&#123;px&#125;\&#125; \times D_&#123;\text&#123;pf&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k]</span> , then  <span class="math">x \in D_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta&#125;</span> .</p>
        <li>If  <span class="math">x \in \&#123;px\&#125; \times D_&#123;pf&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span> , then there exist  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span>  and  <span class="math">\alpha \in R_\beta</span>  such that  <span class="math">x = (px, (\alpha, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)))</span> , so  <span class="math">x \in D_&#123;row, \beta&#125;</span> .</li>
        <li>If  <span class="math">x \in \&#123;rs\&#125; \times L</span> , then there exist  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span>  and  <span class="math">\alpha \in L_\beta</span>  such that  <span class="math">\phi[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu](\alpha, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)) = x</span> , so  <span class="math">x \in D_&#123;row, \beta&#125;</span> .  <span class="math">\square</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">The recursive cover of BS-RS is recursively defined based on the native cover of BS-RS.</p>
      <span id="page-51-2"></span>**Definition G.3.** The recursive cover  $T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  of BS-RS $[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  is the tree of depth  $|\log \dim(L) - \log(k)|$ where, for every non-leaf vertex v labeled by  $(D, BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k])$ , the vertex v has  $|S[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]|$  successors, all labeled by elements of  $S[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  with the natural embedding of their domains into D.
      <span id="page-51-3"></span>**Claim G.4.** The recursive cover of BS-RS[ $\mathbb&#123;K&#125;$ ,  $\mathbb&#123;F&#125;$ , L,  $\mu$ , k] is 1-intersecting (see Definition 4.18).
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> We must show that for every two disconnected vertices u, v it holds that  <span class="math">|\tilde&#123;D&#125;_u \cap \tilde&#123;D&#125;_v| \leq 1</span> . It suffices to do so for every two distinct siblings u, v, because if a is an ancestor of b then  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;D&#125;_a</span>  contains  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;D&#125;_b</span> . Hence, we only need to show that for every two distinct views  <span class="math">(\tilde&#123;D&#125;, \tilde&#123;C&#125;), (\tilde&#123;D&#125;', \tilde&#123;C&#125;')</span>  in the native cover  <span class="math">S[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span> , it holds that  <span class="math">|\tilde&#123;D&#125; \cap \tilde&#123;D&#125;'| \leq 1</span> . First we observe that for every  <span class="math">\alpha_1 \neq \alpha_2 \in L'_0</span>  and  <span class="math">\beta_1 \neq \beta_2 \in L_1</span> , the following sets are disjoint by definition:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li><span class="math">\&#123;\text&#123;px&#125;\&#125; \times \&#123;(\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha_1)\&#125; \times D_&#123;\text&#123;pf&#125;&#125;^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k],</span></li>
        <li><span class="math">\&#123;\operatorname&#123;px&#125;\&#125; \times \&#123;(\operatorname&#123;col&#125;, \alpha_2)\&#125; \times D_&#123;\operatorname&#123;pf&#125;&#125;^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k],</span>   <span class="math">\&#123;\operatorname&#123;px&#125;\&#125; \times \&#123;(\operatorname&#123;row&#125;, \beta_1)\&#125; \times D_&#123;\operatorname&#123;pf&#125;&#125;^&#123;\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta_1&#125;, \mu, k],</span></li>
        <li><span class="math">\&#123;px\&#125; \times \&#123;(row, \beta_2)\&#125; \times D_&#123;pf&#125;^&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta_2&#125;, \mu, k].</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Thus it is enough to show that:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>Any two columns are distinct:  <span class="math">\phi(\alpha_1, \beta_1) \neq \phi(\alpha_2, \beta_2)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\alpha_1 \neq \alpha_2 \in L'_0</span>  and  <span class="math">\beta_1, \beta_2 \in Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)</span> .</li>
        <li>Any two rows are distinct:  <span class="math">\phi(\alpha_1, \beta_1) \neq \phi(\alpha_2, \beta_2)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\beta_1 \neq \beta_2 \in Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)</span> ,  <span class="math">\alpha_1 \in L_&#123;\beta_1&#125;</span> , and  <span class="math">\alpha_2 \in L_&#123;\beta_2&#125;</span> .</li>
        <li>The intersection of any row and column has at most one element:  <span class="math">\phi(\alpha, \beta') \neq \phi(\alpha', \beta)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\alpha, \alpha' \in L'_0</span>  and  <span class="math">\beta, \beta' \in Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)</span>  with  <span class="math">(\alpha', \beta') \neq (\alpha, \beta)</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">But all the above follow from the fact that  <span class="math">\phi[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  is a bijection and, thus, an injection.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">The next claim establishes a connection between the depth of a vertex v in the recursive cover and the independence of the cover  <span class="math">T_v</span>  of the code  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v</span> .</p>
      <span id="page-52-0"></span>Claim G.5. For every vertex v in layer(T,d), the cover  $T_v$  is  $(|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\dim(L)\cdot 2^&#123;-d-1&#125;-\mu-2&#125;)$ -independent. In particular, by assignment, it holds that, for every positive integer m and every non-leaf vertex v in  $T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  with depth less than  $\log_2 \dim(L) - \log_2(\log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125; m + \mu + 2) - 1$ , the cover  $T_v$  is m-independent.
      <p class="text-gray-300">The proof of the above claim directly follows from Claim G.7 and Claim G.6, stated and proved below. The first of these two claims connects the depth of a vertex v and the dimension of a space  <span class="math">L_v</span>  such that  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v = \mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, \mathbb&#123;K&#125;, L_v, \mu, k]</span>  (this claim is used separately also for establishing computational properties in Appendix G.2).</p>
      <span id="page-52-1"></span>**Claim G.6.** If  $v \in \text&#123;layer&#125;(T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k], d)$  then  $\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v = \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, \tilde&#123;L&#125;, \mu, k]$  for some  $\tilde&#123;L&#125;$  such that
      <div class="math-block">\dim(L) \cdot 2^&#123;-d&#125; \le \dim(\tilde&#123;L&#125;) \le \dim(L) \cdot 2^&#123;-d&#125; + 2\mu .</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> The proof is by induction on d. The base case d=0 follows directly from the definition; so we now assume the claim for d-1 and prove it for d. Let  <span class="math">v\in \operatorname&#123;layer&#125;(T,d)</span>  be a vertex of depth d, and let  <span class="math">u\in \operatorname&#123;layer&#125;(T,d-1)</span>  be v's predecessor. By the inductive assumption,  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_u=\operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L_u,\mu,k]</span>  for some  <span class="math">L_u</span>  such that  <span class="math">\dim(L)\cdot 2^&#123;-(d-1)&#125;\leq \dim(L_u)\leq \dim(L)\cdot 2^&#123;-(d-1)&#125;+2\mu</span> .</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">First we argue that  <span class="math">T_u</span>  is not the trivial (singleton) cover. For this, it suffices to show that  <span class="math">\dim(L_u) &gt; k</span> . But this follows from the inductive assumption, since  <span class="math">\operatorname&#123;depth&#125;(T,u) &lt; \lfloor \log \dim(L) - \log(k) \rfloor</span> , so that  <span class="math">\dim(L_u) \geq \dim(L) \cdot 2^&#123;-(\lfloor \log \dim(L) - \log(k) \rfloor - 1)&#125; &gt; 2k</span> .</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Recall  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v = \operatorname&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_v, \mu, k]</span>  for some space  <span class="math">L_v</span> ; we are thus left to show that  <span class="math">\dim(L_u) \cdot 2^&#123;-1&#125; \leq \dim(L_v) \leq \dim(L_u) \cdot 2^&#123;-1&#125; + \mu</span> . We do so by giving two cases, based on the form of  <span class="math">L_v</span> : (a) if  <span class="math">L_v = Z_&#123;L_0[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_u, \mu, k]&#125;(L_1[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_u, \mu, k])</span>  then  <span class="math">\dim(L_v) = \dim(L_1[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_u, \mu, k]) = \lceil \frac&#123;\dim(L_u)&#125;&#123;2&#125; \rceil</span> ; (b) if there exists  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_u, \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">L_v = L_&#123;\beta&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_u, \mu, k]</span>  then  <span class="math">\dim(L_v) = \dim(L_0[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_u, \mu, k]) + \mu = \lfloor \frac&#123;\dim(L_u)&#125;&#123;2&#125; \rfloor + \mu</span> . In either case  <span class="math">\dim(L_u) \cdot 2^&#123;-1&#125; \leq \dim(L_v) \leq \dim(L_v) \cdot 2^&#123;-1&#125; + \mu</span> , and the claim follows.</p>
      <span id="page-52-2"></span>**Claim G.7.** The native cover  $S[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  is  $|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\frac&#123;\dim(L)&#125;&#123;2&#125; - \mu - 2&#125;$ -independent.
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> Recalling Definition 4.16, fix arbitrary subsets  <span class="math">D' \subseteq (\&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;\&#125; \times L'_0) \sqcup (\&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;\&#125; \times L_1)</span>  and  <span class="math">D'' \subseteq D_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  both of size at most  <span class="math">|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\frac&#123;\dim(L)&#125;&#123;2&#125; - \mu - 2&#125;</span> , and define  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;D&#125; := D'' \cup (\cup_&#123;(\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha) \in D'&#125; D_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha&#125;) \cup (\cup_&#123;(\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta) \in D'&#125; D_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta&#125;)</span> . Let  <span class="math">w' \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;&#125;</span>  be such that: (i) for every  <span class="math">(\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha) \in D'</span>  it holds that  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;, \alpha&#125;(w') \in \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span> ; and (ii) for every  <span class="math">(\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta) \in D'</span>  it holds that  <span class="math">\psi_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta&#125;(w') \in \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k]</span> . We need to show that there exists  <span class="math">w \in \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">w|_&#123;\tilde&#123;D&#125;&#125; = w'|_&#123;\tilde&#123;D&#125;&#125;</span> .</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">In fact, it suffices to show that there exists  <span class="math">w_&#123;\square&#125; \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  such that  <span class="math">w_&#123;\square&#125;|_&#123;\tilde&#123;D&#125; \cap D_&#123;\square&#125;&#125; = w'|_&#123;\tilde&#123;D&#125; \cap D_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;</span> , because Claim F.4 implies there exists a unique codeword  <span class="math">w \in \mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  such that  <span class="math">w|_&#123;D_&#123;\square&#125;&#125; = w_&#123;\square&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">w|_&#123;\tilde&#123;D&#125;&#125; = w'|_&#123;\tilde&#123;D&#125;&#125;</span> . Thus, we now argue that there exists  <span class="math">w_&#123;\square&#125; \in \mathrm&#123;RS&#125;_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span>  such that the following holds.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>For every  <span class="math">(\operatorname&#123;col&#125;, \alpha) \in D'</span>  and  <span class="math">\beta \in Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)</span> , it holds that  <span class="math">f_&#123;w_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;(\alpha, \beta) = w'(\phi(\alpha, \beta)) = (\psi_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;, \alpha&#125;(w'))</span>  (rs,  <span class="math">\beta</span> ). In particular,  <span class="math">f_&#123;w_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)&#125; \in \operatorname&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), |L_1| \cdot \rho]</span> , and let  <span class="math">p_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;, \alpha&#125;</span>  be its univariate low degree extension to  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> .</li>
        <li>For every  <span class="math">(\text&#123;row&#125;, \beta) \in D'</span>  and  <span class="math">\alpha \in L_&#123;\beta&#125;</span> , it holds that  <span class="math">f_&#123;w_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;(\alpha, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)) = w'(\phi(\alpha, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta))) = (\psi_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;(w'))</span>  (rs,  <span class="math">\alpha</span> ). In particular,  <span class="math">f_&#123;w_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;|_&#123;L_&#123;\beta&#125; \times \&#123;Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1)\&#125;&#125; \in \text&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, |L_0|]</span> , and let  <span class="math">p_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;</span>  be its univariate low degree extension to  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> .</li>
        <li>For every  <span class="math">(\alpha, \beta) \in D''</span> , it holds that  <span class="math">f_&#123;w_&#123;\square&#125;&#125;(\alpha, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)) = w'(\phi(\alpha, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)))</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">By Definition F.2 it suffices to show that there exists a bivariate polynomial  <span class="math">g \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;[X,Y]</span>  such that: (i)  <span class="math">\deg_X(g) &lt; |L_0|</span> ; (ii)  <span class="math">\deg_Y(g) &lt; |L_1| \cdot \rho</span> ; (iii)  <span class="math">g|_&#123;X=\alpha&#125; = p_&#123;\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;</span>  for every  <span class="math">(\operatorname&#123;col&#125;,\alpha) \in D'</span> ; (iv)  <span class="math">g|_&#123;Y=Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)&#125; = p_&#123;\operatorname&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;</span>  for every  <span class="math">(\operatorname&#123;row&#125;,\beta) \in D'</span> ; (v)  <span class="math">g(\alpha,\beta) = w'(\phi(\alpha,Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(\beta)))</span>  for every  <span class="math">(\alpha,\beta) \in D''</span> . But notice that  <span class="math">|D'| + |D''| \leq 2 \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\frac&#123;\dim(L)&#125;&#123;2&#125; - \mu - 2&#125; = |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\frac&#123;\dim(L)&#125;&#123;2&#125; - \mu - 1&#125; &lt; \min\&#123;|L_0|, |L_1| \cdot \rho\&#125;</span> , because (a)  <span class="math">\log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125;(|L_0|) = \dim(L_0) \geq \frac&#123;\dim(L)&#125;&#123;2&#125; - 1</span> , and (b)  <span class="math">\log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125;(|L_1| \cdot \rho) = \dim(L_1) - \mu \geq \frac&#123;\dim(L)&#125;&#123;2&#125; - \mu</span> . The claim follows by considering a suitable interpolating set (see Section H).</p>
      <h4 id="span-id-page-53-0-span-g-2-computing-spanning-sets-of-dual-codes-in-the-recursive-cover" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2"><span id="page-53-0"></span>G.2 Computing spanning sets of dual codes in the recursive cover</h4>
      <p class="text-gray-300">We prove that spanning sets for duals of codes in the recursive cover can be computed efficiently; this is the key fact that we later use to argue that the algorithm required by Lemma 4.27 satisfies the stated time complexity.</p>
      <span id="page-53-1"></span>**Claim G.8.** For every positive integer m and vertex v in  $T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  of depth at least  $\log_2 \dim(L) - \log_2 \log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125; m$ , a spanning set of  $\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v^&#123;\perp&#125;$  can be computed in time  $\operatorname&#123;poly&#125;(\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125; + m)$ .
      <p class="text-gray-300">The above claim directly follows from Claim G.9 and Claim G.10, stated and proved below.</p>
      <span id="page-53-2"></span>Claim G.9. For every positive integer m and vertex v in  $T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]$  of depth at least  $\log_2 \dim(L) - \log_2 \log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125; m$ ,  $|\tilde&#123;D&#125;_v| \leq \operatorname&#123;poly&#125;(m + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)$ .
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> Ben-Sasson and Sudan [BS08] show that the block length of BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] is  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;O&#125;_&#123;\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mu,k&#125;(|L|)</span>  for any fixed  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mu, k</span> . One can verify that, if we do not fix these parameters, the block length is  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;O&#125;(|L| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)</span> . Next, observe that  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v = \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_v, \mu, k]</span>  for some  <span class="math">L_v</span>  such that  <span class="math">\dim(L_v) \leq \log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125; m + 2\mu</span>  (Claim G.6); in this case, the aforementioned bound becomes  <span class="math">\operatorname&#123;poly&#125;(m + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)</span> .</p>
      <span id="page-53-3"></span>**Claim G.10.** A spanning set for BS-RS[ $\mathbb&#123;K&#125;$ ,  $\mathbb&#123;F&#125;$ , L,  $\mu$ , k] $^&#123;\perp&#125;$  can be found in time poly  $(\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| + |D^&#123;\text&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]|)$ .
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> We show an algorithm that constructs the desired spanning set in the stated time complexity. First, a spanning set for  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,S,d]^&#123;\perp&#125;</span>  can be found in time  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;poly&#125;(\log_2|\mathbb&#123;F&#125;|+|S|)</span> , for any finite field  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , subset  <span class="math">S\subseteq\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , and degree bound d&lt;|S|. Hence, a spanning set for  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;RS&#125;_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu]^&#123;\perp&#125;</span>  can be found in time  <span class="math">(\log_2|\mathbb&#123;F&#125;|\cdot|L|\cdot|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c</span>  for some c&gt;0.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">We argue by induction on  <span class="math">\dim(L)</span>  that a spanning set for BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] <span class="math">^&#123;\perp&#125;</span>  can be found in time  <span class="math">(\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |L| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c</span> . We rely the property that the code BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] is covered by</p>
      <div class="math-block">\&#123;(\mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k], D_&#123;\mathrm&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;)\&#125;_&#123;\alpha \in L'_0&#125; \cup \&#123;(\mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k], D_&#123;\mathrm&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;)\&#125;_&#123;\beta \in L_1&#125;</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300">and the property that  <span class="math">w \in BS\text&#123;-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  if an only if:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li><span class="math">\psi_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;(w) \in \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, Z_&#123;L_0&#125;(L_1), \mu, k]</span>  for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in L'_0</span>  and</li>
        <li><span class="math">\psi_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;(w) \in \text&#123;BS-RS&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L_&#123;\beta&#125;, \mu, k]</span>  for every  <span class="math">\beta \in L_1</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Thus BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;</span> ,  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> , L,  <span class="math">\mu</span> , k] <span class="math">^&#123;\perp&#125;</span>  is spanned by the duals of codes in its cover and, in particular, is spanned by their spanning sets; in sum, it suffices to construct a spanning set for its cover.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">In light of the above, we can bound the construction time of a spanning set for  <span class="math">BS-RS[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]^&#123;\perp&#125;</span>  as follows:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>If  <span class="math">\dim(L) \leq k</span> , the claim follows as the code in this case simply equals  <span class="math">RS_&#123;\square&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu]</span> .</li>
        <li>If  <span class="math">\dim(L) &gt; k</span> , the time to construct a spanning set is at most the time to construct spanning sets for the cover:</li>
      </ul>
      <span id="page-53-7"></span><span id="page-53-6"></span><span id="page-53-5"></span><span id="page-53-4"></span>
      <div class="math-block">|L_0'| \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |L_1| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c + |L_1| \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |L_0'| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu+1&#125;)^c \tag&#123;1&#125;</div>
      <div class="math-block">= |L_0| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu - 1&#125; \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |L_1| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c + |L_1| \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |L_0| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;2\mu&#125;)^c</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300">(2)</p>
      <div class="math-block">= |L| \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c \cdot (|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu-1&#125; \cdot |L_1|^&#123;c-1&#125; + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;c\mu&#125; \cdot |L_0|^&#123;c-1&#125;)</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300">(3)</p>
      <div class="math-block">\leq |L| \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c \cdot \left( |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu+c-2&#125; \cdot |L|^&#123;\frac&#123;c-1&#125;&#123;2&#125;&#125; + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;c\mu&#125; \cdot |L|^&#123;\frac&#123;c-1&#125;&#123;2&#125;&#125; \right) \tag&#123;4&#125;</div>
      <div class="math-block">= |L|^&#123;\frac&#123;c+1&#125;&#123;2&#125;&#125; \cdot (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c \cdot (|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu+c-2&#125; + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;c\mu&#125;)</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300">(5)</p>
      <span id="page-53-8"></span>
      <div class="math-block">\leq (\log_2 |\mathbb&#123;F&#125;| \cdot |L| \cdot |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu&#125;)^c . \tag&#123;6&#125;</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Above, (1) is by the inductive assumption, (2) is by definition of  <span class="math">L'_0</span> , (3) is by the fact that  <span class="math">|L_0| \cdot |L_1| = |L|</span> , and (4) is by definition of  <span class="math">L_0</span> ,  <span class="math">L_1</span> . We are left to show (6), and this follows from the fact that: (i)  <span class="math">\dim(L) &gt; k</span> , (ii)  <span class="math">k &gt; 2\mu</span>  by definition, and (iii) we can choose c to be large enough (namely, so that  <span class="math">|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;\mu+c-2&#125; + |\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^&#123;c\mu&#125; &lt; |L|^&#123;\frac&#123;c-1&#125;&#123;2&#125;&#125;</span>  holds).</p>
      <h4 id="span-id-page-54-0-span-g-3-putting-things-together" class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2"><span id="page-54-0"></span>G.3 Putting things together</h4>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Proof of Lemma 4.27. Define the depth function  <span class="math">d(\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, L, \mu, a) := \log_2 \dim(L) - \log_2(\log_&#123;|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|&#125; a + \mu + 2) - 1</span> . We argue the two conditions in the lemma. First, for every index  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;n&#125; = (\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k), T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k]</span>  is a 1-intersecting recursive cover of BS-RS[ <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k</span> ] (by Claim G.4). Moreover, for every positive integer m and non-leaf vertex v in T with depth <span class="math">(T, v) &lt; d(\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, L, \mu, m)</span> , the cover  <span class="math">T_v</span>  is m-independent (by Claim G.5).</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Second, consider the algorithm that, given an index  <span class="math">\mathbb&#123;n&#125;=(\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu,k)</span>  and subset  <span class="math">I\subseteq D^&#123;\mathrm&#123;BS-RS&#125;&#125;[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,\mathbb&#123;F&#125;,L,\mu,k]</span> , works as follows: (1) for every  <span class="math">\alpha\in I</span>  choose an arbitrary vertex  <span class="math">v_\alpha</span>  in  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;layer&#125;(T,d(\mathbb&#123;K&#125;,L,\mu,|I|))</span>  such that  <span class="math">\alpha\in \tilde&#123;D&#125;_&#123;v_\alpha&#125;</span> , and then set  <span class="math">U:=\&#123;v_\alpha\&#125;_&#123;\alpha\in I&#125;;</span>  (2) compute a spanning set  <span class="math">W_v</span>  set for  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_v^\perp</span> ; (3) return  <span class="math">W:=\cup_&#123;u\in U&#125;W_u</span> . This algorithm satisfies the required properties. First, it runs in time  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;poly&#125;(\log_2|\mathbb&#123;F&#125;|+\dim(L)+|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^\mu+|I|)</span>  because a spanning set set for  <span class="math">\tilde&#123;C&#125;_u^\perp</span>  can be computed in time  <span class="math">\mathrm&#123;poly&#125;(\log_2|\mathbb&#123;F&#125;|+|\mathbb&#123;K&#125;|^\mu+|I|)</span>  (by Claim G.8). Next, its output W meets the requirements:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li><span class="math">U \subseteq \text&#123;layer&#125;(T[\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, \mathbb&#123;F&#125;, L, \mu, k], d(\mathbb&#123;K&#125;, L, \mu, |I|));</span></li>
        <li><span class="math">|U| \leq |I|</span> , by definition of U;</li>
        <li><span class="math">I \subseteq (\bigcup_&#123;u \in U&#125; \tilde&#123;D&#125;_u)</span> , by definition of U;</li>
        <li><span class="math">\operatorname&#123;span&#125;(W) = \operatorname&#123;span&#125;(\bigcup_&#123;u \in U&#125; W_u) = \operatorname&#123;span&#125;(\bigcup_&#123;u \in U&#125; \tilde&#123;C&#125;_u^&#123;\perp&#125;)</span> , by definition of W and  <span class="math">W_u</span> . This completes the proof of Lemma 4.27.</li>
      </ul>
      <h2 id="span-id-page-55-0-span-h-folklore-claim-on-interpolating-sets" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4"><span id="page-55-0"></span>H Folklore claim on interpolating sets</h2>
      <span id="page-55-1"></span>**Claim H.1.** Let  $\mathbb&#123;F&#125;$  be a field, let  $d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;, d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125; \in \mathbb&#123;N&#125;$ , and consider three sets  $S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;, S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125; \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125;$  and  $S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;pnts&#125;&#125; \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125;$  such that  $|S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;| + |S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;| + |S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;pnts&#125;&#125;| \le \min\&#123;d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;, d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;\&#125;$ . Let  $f : \mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125; \to \mathbb&#123;F&#125;$  be a function such that:
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in S_&#123;\text&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span>  there exists  <span class="math">g_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125; \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;&lt; d_&#123;\text&#123;rows&#125;&#125;&#125;[x]</span>  such that  <span class="math">f(\alpha,\beta) = g_&#123;\text&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;(\beta)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\beta \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> ;</li>
        <li>for every  <span class="math">\beta \in S_&#123;\text&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span>  there exists  <span class="math">g_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125; \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;&lt; d_&#123;\text&#123;cols&#125;&#125;&#125;[x]</span>  such that  <span class="math">f(\alpha,\beta) = g_&#123;\text&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;(\alpha)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span> .</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Then there exists  <span class="math">g \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;[X,Y]</span>  such that: (i)  <span class="math">\deg_X(g) &lt; d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span> ; (ii)  <span class="math">\deg_Y(g) &lt; d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span> ; (iii)  <span class="math">g|_&#123;X=\alpha&#125; = g_&#123;\mathsf&#123;col&#125;,\alpha&#125;</span>  for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span> ; (iv)  <span class="math">g|_&#123;Y=\beta&#125; = g_&#123;\mathsf&#123;row&#125;,\beta&#125;</span>  for every  <span class="math">\beta \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span> ; (v)  <span class="math">g(\alpha,\beta) = f(\alpha,\beta)</span>  for every  <span class="math">(\alpha,\beta) \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;pnts&#125;&#125;</span> .</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300"><em>Proof.</em> Any rectangle  <span class="math">D_X \times D_Y \subseteq \mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125;</span>  with  <span class="math">|D_X| = d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">|D_Y| = d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span>  is an interpolating set: for every  <span class="math">w \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D_X \times D_Y&#125;</span>  there exists a unique  <span class="math">g \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;[X,Y]</span>  such that: (i)  <span class="math">\deg_X(g) &lt; d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span> ; (ii)  <span class="math">\deg_Y(g) &lt; d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span> ; (iii)  <span class="math">g|_&#123;D_X \times D_Y&#125; = w</span> . Define</p>
      <div class="math-block">D_X := S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125; \cup \&#123;\alpha : \exists \beta \text&#123; s.t. &#125; (\alpha, \beta) \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;pnts&#125;&#125;\&#125; \quad \text&#123;and&#125; \quad D_Y := S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125; \cup \&#123;\beta : \exists \alpha \text&#123; s.t. &#125; (\alpha, \beta) \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;pnts&#125;&#125;\&#125; .</div>
      <p class="text-gray-300">Note that  <span class="math">|D_X| \leq d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">|D_Y| \leq d_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span> ; if either is strictly smaller, extend it arbitrarily to match the upper bound. Choose  <span class="math">w \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;^&#123;D_X \times D_Y&#125;</span>  to be a word that satisfies: (i)  <span class="math">w(\alpha, \beta) = f(\alpha, \beta)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\alpha \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">\beta \in D_Y</span> ; (ii)  <span class="math">w(\alpha, \beta) = f(\alpha, \beta)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\beta \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">\alpha \in D_X</span> ; (iii)  <span class="math">w(\alpha, \beta) = f(\alpha, \beta)</span>  for every  <span class="math">\beta \in S_&#123;\mathsf&#123;pnts&#125;&#125;</span> . Denote by  <span class="math">g_w \in \mathbb&#123;F&#125;[X, Y]</span>  the unique "low degree extension" of w; we show that  <span class="math">g_w</span>  satisfies the requirements of the claim.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-300">The degree bounds and the equivalence on  <span class="math">S_&#123;pnts&#125;</span>  follows by definition of  <span class="math">g_w</span> ; thus it suffices to show equivalence of  <span class="math">g_w</span>  with f when restricted to the required rows and columns.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-1 my-2">
        <li>For every  <span class="math">\alpha \in S_&#123;\text&#123;cols&#125;&#125;</span> : it holds by definition of  <span class="math">g_w</span>  that  <span class="math">g_w|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times D_Y&#125; = f|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times D_Y&#125;</span> ; moreover,  <span class="math">g_w|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125;&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">f|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125;&#125;</span>  are evaluations of polynomials of degree less than  <span class="math">|D_Y|</span> , which implies that  <span class="math">g_w|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125;&#125; = f|_&#123;\&#123;\alpha\&#125; \times \mathbb&#123;F&#125;&#125;</span> .</li>
        <li>For every  <span class="math">\beta \in S_&#123;\text&#123;rows&#125;&#125;</span> : it holds by definition of  <span class="math">g_w</span>  that  <span class="math">g_w|_&#123;D_X \times \&#123;\beta\&#125;&#125; = f|_&#123;D_X \times \&#123;\beta\&#125;&#125;</span> ; moreover,  <span class="math">g_w|_&#123;\mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \&#123;\beta\&#125;&#125;</span>  and  <span class="math">f|_&#123;\mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \&#123;\beta\&#125;&#125;</span>  are evaluations of polynomials of degree less than  <span class="math">|D_X|</span> , which implies that  <span class="math">g_w|_&#123;\mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \&#123;\beta\&#125;&#125; = f|_&#123;\mathbb&#123;F&#125; \times \&#123;\beta\&#125;&#125;</span> .</li>
      </ul>
